<provider> can be provider name or url

Revoke:
mytoken revoke [--provider=<provider>] [--name=<name>] [OPTIONS]
mytoken revoke --ST=<ST> [OPTIONS]
OPTIONS:  --recursive

AT:
mytoken AT [--provider=<provider>] [--name=<name>] [<comment>] [OPTIONS]
mytoken AT --ST=<ST> [<comment>] [OPTIONS]
OPTIONS: Scopes, audience
Note: If the used ST does not have the AT capability, but can create a ST that has it, do so

ST:
mytoken ST [NAME] --ST=<ST> [OPTIONS]
mytoken ST [NAME] --TC=<TC> [OPTIONS]
mytoken ST [NAME] [--provider=<provider>] [--name=<name>]
mytoken ST [NAME] --oidc[=<flow>] [--provider=<provider>]
OPTIONS: --store, capabilities, subtoken_capabilities, restrictions, token-type (only if not --store)
On restrictions:
    - required parameter if --store is not used (use --restrictions=none to not use any restrictions without storing the ST)
    - option to read restrictions as json from file
    - option to start passing of multiple restriction clauses, e.g. --restrictions=start
    - just one restriction clause, --restrictions can be omitted, but at least one of the clause parameter required (if required)
    - A clause has these parameters: --nbf --exp --scope --audience --ip --geoip-white --geoip-black --usages-AT --usages-other
        - Nice syntax sugar for time values: e.g. take unix time stamp, but also something like '11.4.2021_14:00:00' (absolute time in a more readable format) and a relative time, e.g. '+7d'
